Hm. An alternate idea is a decorator or subclass that exposes 
&quot;assertInvariants()&quot;. This appears to me the best of both worlds: the 
original class exposes the invariant conditions as protected methods, so 
they are not available in other packages; however they are available to 
the subclass, which can live in the testing package.

class Thing {
    protected boolean isInvariant1True() { ... }
    protected boolean isInvariant2True() { ... }
    ...
    protected boolean isInvariantNTrue() { ... }
}

class TestableThing extends Thing {
    public void assertInvariants() {
        return isInvariant1True() && ....;
    }
}

class ThingTest extends TestCase {
    private TestableThing createThing(...) {
        return new TestableThing(...);
    }
    ....
    public void testSomething() {
        final TestableThing thing = createThing(....);
        thing.assertInvariants();
        ....
    }
}

True, there is dead production code in Thing, but at least it&#39;s not 
public, dead production code!

JBR.

Robertson, Don wrote:

&gt; Let&#39;s assume that invoking an assertInvariants() method within your 
&gt; class&#39;s methods is too expensive to be practical, but you want it for 
&gt; the purpose of unit testing anyway. Would it be structurally superior to :
&gt;
&gt; 1) Implement such a method within the actual class and invoke it from 
&gt; the test case. The main benefits I see are minimal exposure of the 
&gt; class&#39;s internals (although it *is* white box testing after all), and 
&gt; visual proximity of the invariant conditions for 
&gt; implementors/modifiers. The negative is that there is &quot;dead code&quot; 
&gt; (from a runtime perspective) within the class.
&gt;
&gt; 2) Allow access to internal state within the class and write the 
&gt; assertInvariants() method within the test class(es). The benefits are 
&gt; visual proximity of the invariant conditions with the other functional 
&gt; description of the class, and no dead code in the runtime class. The 
&gt; negative is the need for exposure of more internal state.
&gt;
&gt; Opinions?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; A second &quot;meta&quot; question might be whether you think it is worthwhile 
&gt; to check invariant conditions within your unit tests as a default 
&gt; behavior, or is it overkill?
&gt;
&gt; Don
